child.pub-comments: On his map, Wurm (1972) uses a dashed line for the border of Karantyic, of the same weight as the solid lines used to indicate distinct groups within the same family. He does not indicate what this means, but presumably it indicates doubt as to whether Karantyic should be its own group or whether it should be part of an adjacent group such as Pama-Maric. He also includes a question mark next to the name.

child.pub-comments: On his map, Wurm (1972) uses a dashed line for the border of Karantyic, of the same weight as the solid lines used to indicate distinct groups within the same family. He does not indicate what this means, but presumably it indicates doubt as to whether Walangama should be its own group or whether it should be part of an adjacent group such as Pama-Maric. He also places a question mark next to the name. Wurm generally seems clear that everything at this level of organization is to be a group, but the dashed border and the question mark indicate a general lack of sureness about what Walangama consists of, so I've chosen to use the already existing language code from our database rather than proliferate unnecessary subgroup codes without evidence. Note also that Wurm names the majority of "groups" with an -ic suffix, which Walangama lacks.

root.pub-comments: Wurm (1972) uses the name "Common Australian" to refer to an extinct proto-language from which all Australian languages are descended. He also occasionally refers to Pama-Nyungan, etc. as "Australian phylic families", presumably invoking the theory of the Australian Macro-Phylum (O'Grady, Voegelin, Voegelin 1966). This tree is primarily based on a map from Wurm (1972: 166); an LL-MAP version is available at http://llmap.org/viewer.html?maps=354024.
